  <li id="comment-21230" class="comment even thread-even depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="https://www.blogger.com/profile/00225685623822099930" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">Grace</a></cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2010/10/now-here-now-there/#comment-21230"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2010-10-25T20:07:13-04:00">Monday, October 25, 2010 at 8:07 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>In August I bought a dozen oysters from Taylor Shellfish and grilled them in a Capitol Hill courtyard overlooking Seattle. They were delicious, briny, fresh, and tender after about 3 minutes on the covered grill&#8211;the perfect accompaniment for a summer sunset in Seattle. I recommend grilled oysters with any kind of dipping sauce (butter and herb, cocktail, hot, olive oil and herb) for squeamish eaters. </p>
<p>You could also try hangtown fry (scrambled eggs and oysters), the historic treat of California miners and loggers.</p>
    </div>

